    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e3ea95c7-4ac8-4cf9-a635-59817c2a8f5c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old Czech woman with a slender build, dark shoulder-length hair, and tired, light-sensitive eyes. She works as a graphic designer at a Prague-based advertising agency, spending long hours in front of multiple screens in a brightly lit open-plan office. She lives with her partner and their young daughter in a flat in Vinohrady. In her limited free time she enjoys yoga, reading, and visiting weekend farmers' markets with her family.\n\n{patientName} presents with a several-year history of recurrent, episodic headaches predominantly affecting the right side of her head in the temporal and ear region [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2], with a throbbing character [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2]. Episodes last from a few hours to over 36 hours [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2] and are accompanied by nausea [SNOMED:G43.9], vomiting [SNOMED:G43.9], photophobia [SNOMED:G43.9], and occasional burping [SNOMED:G43.9]. She reports that attacks are particularly debilitating, often forcing her to retreat to a dark, quiet room and miss work.\n\n{patientName} identifies stress, disrupted sleep, and prolonged screen exposure as personal triggers. She has also noticed that attacks tend to occur perimenstrually. She does not smoke, drinks alcohol only occasionally, and tries to maintain a balanced diet, though she admits to frequent coffee consumption. She has a close network of friends and a supportive partner, but the migraine episodes significantly impact her social life and professional productivity."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:cf72bbff-c36f-4380-874a-df77a28d746b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a known diagnosis of irritable bowel syndrome (IBS), a recognised comorbidity of migraine thought to share underlying gut-brain axis dysfunction [PMID:38108544]. She is managed with mebeverine for IBS-related spasms and omeprazole for occasional dyspeptic symptoms. She takes naproxen on an as-needed basis for dysmenorrhoea [MEDDIALOG:G43.9:2]. There is no prior hospitalisation for neurological events. She underwent a neurological examination two years ago, which was unremarkable, and a brain MRI was performed to exclude secondary causes of headache, returning a normal result. An electroencephalography was also performed during initial headache workup. {patientName} has a strong maternal family history of migraine, consistent with the known genetic predisposition to the condition [PMID:12720601]. She does not use tobacco and drinks alcohol infrequently. She has no history of cardiovascular disease, coagulopathy, or use of direct oral anticoagulants [PMID:37582651]. She is not currently using oral contraceptives."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
